1

00:00:01,700  -->  00:00:04,290
Just using what you know from

2

00:00:04,290  -->  00:00:07,900
the bivariate case of comparing two variables in the last lesson,

3

00:00:07,900  -->  00:00:12,320
you probably know more than you think about multiple linear regression models.

4

00:00:12,320  -->  00:00:17,170
It's essentially the same as with using only one explanatory variable,

5

00:00:17,170  -->  00:00:19,960
except that when you interpret your coefficients,

6

00:00:19,960  -->  00:00:24,125
you'll add the statement of holding all other variables constant.

7

00:00:24,125  -->  00:00:26,200
What exactly does this mean?

8

00:00:26,200  -->  00:00:28,280
Well, if you were to interpret

9

00:00:28,280  -->  00:00:31,320
this coefficient attached to the square footage of the house,

10

00:00:31,320  -->  00:00:35,660
we would say for each additional unit increase in the area of the house,

11

00:00:35,660  -->  00:00:37,800
the price is expected to increase by

12

00:00:37,800  -->  00:00:42,935
345.9 as long as all the other variables stay the same.

13

00:00:42,935  -->  00:00:47,930
Assuming that these houses both have one bathroom, one bedroom,

14

00:00:47,930  -->  00:00:51,360
but one house has one square foot more than the other,

15

00:00:51,360  -->  00:00:55,565
we would expect its price to be 345.9 higher.

16

00:00:55,565  -->  00:01:00,270
This interpretation, which is almost exactly the same in the earlier lesson,

17

00:01:00,270  -->  00:01:03,690
is what you would do for every quantitative variable

18

00:01:03,690  -->  00:01:06,125
in our multiple linear regression model.

19

00:01:06,125  -->  00:01:10,160
Additionally, a quick glance at the P values can provide

20

00:01:10,160  -->  00:01:12,380
some context for whether or not we think

21

00:01:12,380  -->  00:01:15,280
a variable is statistically related to the response.

22

00:01:15,280  -->  00:01:17,540
This isn't the only check you should do,

23

00:01:17,540  -->  00:01:22,780
but it's a great quick check to understand which relationships appear to be important.

24

00:01:22,780  -->  00:01:26,540
Two points for further exploration come from these exercises.

25

00:01:26,540  -->  00:01:30,500
First, notice that even though looking at the relationship between

26

00:01:30,500  -->  00:01:32,500
only the number of bathrooms and

27

00:01:32,500  -->  00:01:35,740
the price showed a statistically significant relationship.

28

00:01:35,740  -->  00:01:37,920
When we added this to looking at

29

00:01:37,920  -->  00:01:41,520
all the variables at once, this relationship disappeared.

30

00:01:41,520  -->  00:01:43,940
There are a few reasons why this might have happened,

31

00:01:43,940  -->  00:01:46,335
and we'll explore those in the next concept.

32

00:01:46,335  -->  00:01:50,350
Second, when adding quantitative variables to our model,

33

00:01:50,350  -->  00:01:53,030
it worked just like you saw in the last lesson.

34

00:01:53,030  -->  00:01:55,250
But what about with categorical variables?

35

00:01:55,250  -->  00:01:58,250
When we tried to add them, everything broke.

36

00:01:58,250  -->  00:02:02,530
Let's explore these two findings a little bit more closely.
